[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Git Flow recommends a branching strategy that uses multiple long-lived branches, including a main branch for production-ready code, a develop branch for integration of features, and separate branches for features, releases, and hotfixes.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Git Flow is a branching model that uses multiple long-lived branches: main, develop, feature, release, and hotfix branches.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In contrast, trunk-based development uses a single main branch where developers integrate their changes frequently, often multiple times a day, minimizing the use of long-lived branches.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Trunk-based development uses a single main branch where developers integrate their changes frequently, often multiple times a day.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "For large software teams, trunk-based development is generally preferred because it reduces integration problems and encourages continuous integration, whereas Git Flow's multiple long-lived branches can lead to complex merges and integration challenges.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Trunk-based development is generally preferred for large teams because it reduces integration problems and encourages continuous integration.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Git Flow's multiple long-lived branches can lead to complex merges and integration challenges.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In Test-Driven Development (TDD), the exact sequence of the Red-Green-Refactor cycle is as follows: first, write a failing test (Red), then write just enough code to make the test pass (Green), and finally refactor the code to improve its structure without changing its behavior (Refactor).",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The Red-Green-Refactor cycle is a fundamental part of TDD: write a failing test (Red), write code to pass the test (Green), then refactor the code (Refactor).",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "It is recommended to perform multiple test iterations in this cycle before committing code, typically around three to five iterations, to ensure the code is well-tested and clean.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Developers typically perform three to five Red-Green-Refactor cycles before committing code to ensure quality and stability.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO/IEC 25010 quality model, also known as ISO 9126, defines a set of quality characteristics that replace the older McCall quality factors.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One major difference between the ISO model and those of McCall and Boehm is that the ISO hierarchy is strict: each right-hand characteristic is related only to exactly one left-hand attribute.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The ISO 9126 model includes the following top-level quality characteristics: Functionality, Reliability, Usability, Efficiency, Maintainability, and Portability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_5161_5161_1179"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "McCall's quality factors include Correctness, Reliability, Efficiency, Integrity, Usability, Maintainability, Testability, Flexibility, Portability, Reusability, and Interoperability.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "img",
                "content": null,
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_188_188_57"
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The two models map to each other in that each ISO 9126 characteristic corresponds to one or more McCall quality factors, but the ISO model is more strictly hierarchical with each right-hand characteristic related to exactly one left-hand attribute.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "One major difference between the ISO model and those of McCall and Boehm is that the ISO hierarchy is strict: each right-hand characteristic is related only to exactly one left-hand attribute.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

