[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The provided context does not explicitly mention Domain-Driven Design (DDD) or the concept of a \"Bounded Context.\"",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "The provided context does not explicitly mention Domain-Driven Design (DDD) or the concept of a \"Bounded Context.\"",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "However, the context discusses decomposition of a system into software units through various architectural views and design methods, such as modular decomposition, data-oriented decomposition, functional decomposition, and object-oriented design.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "We want to decompose the system's design into its constituent programmable units, such as modules, objects, or procedures.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Wasserman (1996) points out that there are at least five ways that we can partition the system into units: modular decomposition: based on assigning functions to modules; data-oriented decomposition: based on external data structures; event-oriented decomposition: based on events that the system must handle; outside-in design: based on user inputs to the system; object-oriented design: based on identifying classes of objects and their interrelationships.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "In a layered architecture, decomposition views portray the system as programmable units, often hierarchically organized, and mappings among views show how these units relate to runtime components and other architectural elements.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Decomposition view: This traditional view of a system's decomposition portrays the system as programmable units. As depicted in Figure 5.5, this view is likely to be hierarchical and may be represented by multiple models.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Such a mapping reveals all of the units needed to implement each layer.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    },
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "Therefore, while the concept of a \"Bounded Context\" in DDD is not directly addressed, it can be related to the idea of defining clear boundaries for software units or modules within a layered architecture, where each unit encapsulates specific functionality or data, and the relationships and dependencies among these units are explicitly managed and documented.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "A system's architecture describes the system in terms of a set of architectural units, and a map of how the units relate to one another. The more independent the units, the more modular the architecture and the more easily we can design and develop the pieces separately.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ],
        "type": null
    }
]

[
    {
        "role": "paragraph",
        "segment": "The textbook recommends several machine learning techniques for automating effort estimation beyond the COCOMO II model.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "In general, this 'learning' approach has been tried in different ways by other researchers.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet_intro",
        "segment": "These techniques include",
        "citations": []
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Neural networks, which have produced more accurate predictions than the original COCOMO and SLIM models.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Srinivasan and Fisher (1995) used Kemerer's data (Kemerer 1989) with a statistical technique called a regression tree; they produced predictions more accurate than those of the original COCOMO model and SLIM, a proprietary commercial model. However, their results were not as good as those produced by a neural network or a model based on function points.",
                "img_id": null
            },
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "[FIGURE 3.13 Shepperd's feed-forward neural network.]",
                "img_id": "img0_se_theory_practice.pdf__chunk_1042_1043_257"
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Regression trees, which have been used to produce predictions more accurate than the original COCOMO model and SLIM.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Srinivasan and Fisher (1995) used Kemerer's data (Kemerer 1989) with a statistical technique called a regression tree; they produced predictions more accurate than those of the original COCOMO model and SLIM, a proprietary commercial model.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Tree induction techniques, which have obtained better results using datasets like Kemerer and COCOMO.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Briand, Basili, and Thomas (1992) obtained better results from using a tree induction technique, using the Kemerer and COCOMO datasets.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "role": "bullet",
        "segment": "Decision trees, which can identify project, process, and product characteristics useful in predicting effort and fault-prone modules.",
        "citations": [
            {
                "type": "source_text",
                "content": "Porter and Selby (1990) also used a tree-based approach; they constructed a decision tree that identifies which project, process, and product characteristics may be useful in predicting likely effort. They also used the technique to predict which modules are likely to be fault-prone.",
                "img_id": null
            }
        ]
    }
]

